<center>
<H2><FONT COLOR="red">Goals</FONT></H2>
</center>

<p>

The existing BLAS have proven to be very effective in assisting portable,
efficient software for sequential, vector and shared memory 
high-performance computers.  
We have decided to establish a Forum to consider expanding the BLAS
in a number of ways in light of modern software, language, and
hardware developments.
<p>

Goals:</p>
<UL>
<li>
  Stimulate thought,
<li>
  Discussion, 
<li> 
  Functionality and
<li>
  Future development of a set of standards for basic matrix
  data structures,
<li>
  Both dense and sparse,
<li>
  Calling sequences for a set of low-level computational kernels for 
  the parallel and sequential settings.
</UL>
<P>

Major aims of these standards will be to enable linear algebra
libraries (both public domain and commercial) to interoperate
efficiently and easily.
 
 
Numerical methods for dense matrices on parallel computers require high
efficiency kernels that provide functionality similar to that in
traditional BLAS on sequential machines.
We have begun the forum with a discussion of
the  need for a light weight interface to much of the functionality
of traditional BLAS. In addition, iterative and sparse direct methods
require additional functionality not in traditional BLAS.


<p>
Who should be viewed as the end users of the interfaces developed by the
forum? computer vendors (both hardware and software), 
average application programmers, higher level library writers?
We would like to get your input on these questions as well as
what you would like to see in a set of basic operations for linear algebra.
